Yes — in Spring Data Redis 4, `GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer` is deprecated. Use:

```java
GenericJacksonJsonRedisSerializer
```

Spring’s deprecated API list says `GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer` is deprecated since 4.0 in favor of `GenericJacksonJsonRedisSerializer`. ([Home][1])

Use this:

```java
import org.springframework.data.redis.serializer.GenericJacksonJsonRedisSerializer;
import org.springframework.data.redis.serializer.StringRedisSerializer;
```

```java
@Bean
public RedisTemplate<String, Object> redisTemplate(
        RedisConnectionFactory connectionFactory) {

    RedisTemplate<String, Object> template = new RedisTemplate<>();
    template.setConnectionFactory(connectionFactory);

    StringRedisSerializer stringSerializer = new StringRedisSerializer();
    GenericJacksonJsonRedisSerializer jsonSerializer =
            new GenericJacksonJsonRedisSerializer();

    template.setKeySerializer(stringSerializer);
    template.setHashKeySerializer(stringSerializer);
    template.setValueSerializer(jsonSerializer);
    template.setHashValueSerializer(jsonSerializer);

    template.afterPropertiesSet();

    return template;
}
```

Do **not** pass `com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper` if your constructor expects `tools.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper`.

For now, remove the custom `ObjectMapper` from the Redis serializer and use the no-args constructor.

